{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17520557","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17520557"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:26:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:26:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13214"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13214","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13214"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.32,0.4,0.19,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5650"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103626"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5650","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5650"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13214"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86043"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"107"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"4923"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"6523"},{"type":"tags","id":"6610"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9636"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10561"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14866"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35904"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42856"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44389"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103626","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103626"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of a painful swollen left leg. He has had several previous hospital admissions for the same problem. He has a medical history of type 2 diabetes for which he takes metformin. He does not take any other regular medications and has experienced angioedema to penicillin in the past.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 128/82 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.6\u00b0C. His left leg is erythematous, diffusely swollen up to the shin and several areas of superficial ulceration are clearly visible (Image). There is generalised tenderness and the leg is warm compared to the other leg. All peripheral pulses are palpable. A random blood glucose is 11.7 mmol/L.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis laboratory investigations show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin 160 g/L (135-175)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count 15 x 10^9/L (4-11)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelets 200 x 10^9/L (150-450)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EC-reactive protein 23.8 mg/dL (0.3-1.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECulture of the wound reveals gram-positive cocci in chains that produce a clear area on the blood agar.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Metronidazole","Amoxicillin plus clavulanic acid","Clindamycin","Meropenem","Doxycycline"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical features consistent with cellulitis in the context of poorly controlled diabetes. The wound culture findings suggest \u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus pyogenes\u003C/em\u003E as the likely causative organism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECellulitis is an acute bacterial infection of the deep dermis and surrounding subcutaneous tissue. In diabetic patients, the foot is particularly vulnerable due to impaired immunity, neuropathy, and compromised blood flow. \u003Cstrong\u003EStreptococcus pyogenes\u003C/strong\u003E is the most common cause of cellulitis, followed by \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClindamycin\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate treatment in this case. It provides excellent coverage against \u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus pyogenes\u003C/em\u003E and is the preferred option for patients with penicillin allergy (note also that trimethoprim+sulfamethoxazole can be used instead of clindamycin). Clindamycin also has good tissue penetration, which is important in treating deep soft tissue infections like cellulitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmoxicillin plus clavulanic acid\u003C/strong\u003E would be an excellent choice for cellulitis in most cases, but it is contraindicated here due to the patient\u0027s history of penicillin allergy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetronidazole\u003C/strong\u003E primarily covers anaerobic bacteria and is not effective against \u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus pyogenes\u003C/em\u003E, which is an aerobic organism. It would not be an appropriate choice for this case of cellulitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMeropenem\u003C/strong\u003E is a broad-spectrum antibiotic typically reserved for more severe infections or when multidrug-resistant organisms are suspected. While it would cover \u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus pyogenes\u003C/em\u003E, it\u0027s unnecessarily broad for this case and should be reserved for more complex infections to prevent antimicrobial resistance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDoxycycline\u003C/strong\u003E has limited activity against \u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus pyogenes\u003C/em\u003E and is not a first-line choice for cellulitis caused by this organism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn addition to antibiotic therapy, management should include glycemic control, elevation of the affected limb, and monitoring for progression of infection. To prevent recurrence, it\u0027s crucial to optimize diabetes management through regular follow-up, HbA1c monitoring, and comprehensive diabetes education.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Streptococcus pyogenes is the most common cause of cellulitis, followed by Staphylococcus aureus.","Penicillin is the first choice for cellulitis, but in patients who are allergic to penicillin, clindamycin is preferred."],"references":["Salleo E, MacKay CI, Cannon J, et al. Cellulitis in children: a retrospective single centre study from AustraliaBMJ Paediatrics Open 2021;5:e001130. Available at: https://bmjpaedsopen.bmj.com/content/5/1/e001130","Brown BD, Hood Watson KL. Cellulitis. [Updated 2022 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan-. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK549770/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86043"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13214"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20330"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20330","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20330"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/xoMBk9FsuLoc5Z91xab6cDF1Xc97r1.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/xoMBk9FsuLoc5Z91xab6cDF1Xc97r1.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":600,"height":377}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86043","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86043"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-24T21:24:34+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-24T